This looks wrong.  One board doesn't have 3 NVMe devices physically embedded.  I suspect you need 2 files, one for this board, and one for the NVME drive that's detected.
Hi Ed, in our HDD board, it does have 4 SSDs on one board.

It has 4 SSDs or it has 4 slots for SSDs?  What Ed is getting at here is that you've instantiated NVMe-MI sensors for devices that might not be present.  Should we have a separate config for the SSDs themselves?
Move NVMe configs into a seperate file `catalina_hdd_nvme.json`.
Please also add a manufacturer field check.
Done
What triggers off of this?

Hi Matt, we reference the implementation from here (https://github.com/NVIDIA/dbus-sensors/blob/develop/src/SatelliteSensor.cpp#L48-L49), and manual apply the patch into dbus-sensors to support "SatelliteSensor".

Please remove all stanzas of this type and put in their own patchset, which can be merged once the satellite implementation is merged in openbmc/dbus-sensors.

You've pointed to a fork, which is fine, you're welcome to implement things in forks, but putting those same configs in upstream removes the possibility for review.  For example "Satellite" is far less detailed of a type name that we would likely accept.

Got it, I moved all "Satellite" to another commmit and keep it as WIP for now.

nevermind, this is for bmcweb aggregation
Yeah, we really should've picked a better name for this.  Probably an opportunity to change in the future.  Something like "RedfishHttpService" or something like that.

Should this be "Catalina HDD Carrier" then?

This isn't a separate FRU though.

Hi Patrick, 
I am not full follow your comment, could you share more information or example?

There is no "Catalina HDD NVMe".  You have a carrier that has SSDs plugged into it.  The carrier has a FRU EEPROM and is detected (you've changed the name to carrier on that one, which is good).  The SSDs themselves have their own detection method (eeprom?) and locations.  What you've written here attempted to make a fake Inventory item with 4 SSD sensors, but this isn't a real thing.  You'd need to add detection for each SSD independently, which will also deal with partial populated carrier cards.

Hi Ed & Patrick,
I will have a check the method of detecting SSD, I remove `catalina_hdd_nvme.json` for now and will add it back in new commit.

Could you help review the remaining part? Thank you.
Should this be "Catalina OSFP Carrier" then?
Done
